<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,533,1137]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,467,608,633]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">External morphology.</emphasis>
Thinly encrusting, covering up to 
<quantity box="[899,975,608,633]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="cm" value="60.0">60 cm</quantity>
<number box="[975,983,605,619]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" value="2.0">2</number>
substratum. Soft consistency, slightly mucous; smooth surface, except for protruding substrate structure and a few subectosomal canals; numerous, very small (ca. 
<quantity box="[270,340,680,704]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
) oscula. Bright red, uniform color in life, only oscular rims being slightly less pigmented (appearing pink).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,533,1137]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,429,752,777]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Skeleton structure.</emphasis>
Disorderly strands of spongin cored and echinated by (sub-)tylostyles; in places, these megascleres are arranged in criss-cross fashion. Microscleres were found throughout the ecto- and choanosome. An irregular network of spongin fibers cored by (sub-) tylostyles, echinated by stubby acanthostyles. Smaller tylostyles are in the ectosome, some forming brushes at the surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,533,1137]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,896,921]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Spicules.</emphasis>
